ing researchers in different disciplines; analyses case studies of innovative research projects where ethics have been central to the researcher-subject relationship; assesses the impact of ethics on research methods and approaches; provides useful comparisons of research conducted by professionals and service-users; offers a unique insight into research participants' perspectives, which are so often absent in discussions of research ethics. This book is essential reading for researchers who are concerned about the ethical quality of their interactions with their subjects, research funders and those engaged in research governance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aApplied ethicsxStudy and teaching. 0aResearchxMoral and ethical aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Methodology.2bisacsh1 aAbrahams (HA), Hilary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Pat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAshcroft, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCameron, Ailsa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodenough, Trudy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGramlich, Stacey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHague (GH), Gill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenderson, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKent, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKent, Naomi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLloyd, Liz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalos (EM), Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCarry (MM), Melanie, econtributor.